  <main>
    <div class="qa-page">

      <div class="qa-header">
        <div class="page-eyebrow">
          <svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="22 12 18 12 15 21 9 3 6 12 2 12"/></svg>
          Retirement Guide
        </div>
        <h1>401(k) Contribution Limits 2025: How Much Can You Contribute?</h1>
        <p class="qa-meta">Updated April 2026 &nbsp;|&nbsp; Based on IRS Notice 2024-80 &nbsp;|&nbsp; Tax year 2025</p>
        <p>The IRS increased 401(k) contribution limits for 2025. Employees can contribute up to $23,500 to a traditional or Roth 401(k), up from $23,000 in 2024. Workers aged 50 and older can add a catch-up contribution of $7,500, bringing their total to $31,000. The combined limit including employer contributions rises to $70,000.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="ad-zone">
        <div class="ad-zone-label">Advertisement</div>
        <ins class="adsbygoogle" style="display:block"
          data-ad-client="ca-pub-5193834725888549"
          data-ad-slot="5205436277"
          data-ad-format="auto"
          data-full-width-responsive="true"></ins>
        <script>(adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});</script>
      </div>

      <div class="qa-section">
        <div class="section-eyebrow">2025 Limits</div>
        <h2>Employee Contribution Limits</h2>
        <p>For 2025, the IRS sets the following 401(k) contribution limits:</p>
        <table class="bracket-table" style="margin-top:14px">
          <thead><tr><th>Contribution Type</th><th>2025 Limit</th><th>2024 Limit</th><th>Change</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Employee elective deferrals (under 50)</td><td><strong>$23,500</strong></td><td>$23,000</td><td style="color:#16a34a">+$500</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Catch-up contribution (age 50–59, 64+)</td><td><strong>$7,500</strong></td><td>$7,500</td><td style="color:#6b7280">No change</td></tr>
            <tr><td>SECURE 2.0 super catch-up (age 60–63)</td><td><strong>$11,250</strong></td><td>N/A</td><td style="color:#16a34a">New for 2025</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Total employee contribution (age 50+)</td><td><strong>$31,000</strong></td><td>$30,500</td><td style="color:#16a34a">+$500</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Combined employee + employer limit</td><td><strong>$70,000</strong></td><td>$69,000</td><td style="color:#16a34a">+$1,000</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Combined limit (age 60–63)</td><td><strong>$81,250</strong></td><td>N/A</td><td style="color:#16a34a">New for 2025</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p>These limits apply to 401(k), 403(b), most 457 plans, and the federal Thrift Savings Plan. Contributions must be made through payroll deduction by December 31, 2025.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="qa-section">
        <div class="section-eyebrow">Traditional vs Roth</div>
        <h2>Traditional 401(k) vs Roth 401(k)</h2>
        <p>Most employers offer both a traditional and Roth 401(k) option. The $23,500 contribution limit is shared between them — you can split contributions any way you like, but the combined total cannot exceed the annual limit.</p>
        <div class="compare-grid">
          <div class="compare-card lt">
            <h3>Traditional 401(k)</h3>
            <div class="compare-row"><span>Contributions</span><span>Pre-tax</span></div>
            <div class="compare-row"><span>Reduces income now?</span><span>Yes</span></div>
            <div class="compare-row"><span>Withdrawals taxed?</span><span>Yes, as ordinary income</span></div>
            <div class="compare-row"><span>Best when</span><span>Higher income now than in retirement</span></div>
          </div>
          <div class="compare-card st">
            <h3>Roth 401(k)</h3>
            <div class="compare-row"><span>Contributions</span><span>After-tax</span></div>
            <div class="compare-row"><span>Reduces income now?</span><span>No</span></div>
            <div class="compare-row"><span>Withdrawals taxed?</span><span>No (qualified withdrawals)</span></div>
            <div class="compare-row"><span>Best when</span><span>Lower income now than in retirement</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tip-callout"><p><strong>Always capture the full employer match first.</strong> If your employer matches contributions, contribute at least enough to get the full match before deciding between traditional and Roth. Employer matches are free money and do not count toward your personal $23,500 limit.</p></div>
      </div>

      <div class="ad-zone">
        <div class="ad-zone-label">Advertisement</div>
        <ins class="adsbygoogle" style="display:block"
          data-ad-client="ca-pub-5193834725888549"
          data-ad-slot="5205436277"
          data-ad-format="auto"
          data-full-width-responsive="true"></ins>
        <script>(adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({{}});</script>
