      <div class="qa-section">
        <div class="section-eyebrow">Tax Impact</div>
        <h2>How 401(k) Contributions Reduce Your Tax Bill</h2>
        <p>Traditional 401(k) contributions reduce your adjusted gross income dollar for dollar. This can drop you into a lower bracket or reduce the portion of income taxed at a higher rate.</p>
        <div class="example-calc">
          <h3>Example: Single filer, $85,000 salary, $23,500 traditional 401(k) contribution</h3>
          <div class="example-row"><span class="label">Gross salary</span><span class="value">$85,000</span></div>
          <div class="example-row"><span class="label">401(k) contribution</span><span class="value" style="color:#dc2626">&#8722;$23,500</span></div>
          <div class="example-row"><span class="label">Standard deduction (2025)</span><span class="value" style="color:#dc2626">&#8722;$15,000</span></div>
          <div class="example-row"><span class="label">Taxable income</span><span class="value">$46,500</span></div>
          <div class="example-row total"><span class="label">Estimated federal tax</span><span class="value">~$5,253</span></div>
        </div>
        <p>Without the 401(k) contribution, taxable income would be $70,000 and estimated federal tax would be approximately $9,603 — a difference of roughly $4,350 saved. In the 22% bracket, every $1,000 contributed saves approximately $220 in federal tax.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="qa-section">
        <div class="section-eyebrow">Employer Match</div>
        <h2>Employer Matching Contributions</h2>
        <p>Many employers match a percentage of employee contributions — typically 50% to 100% of contributions up to 3–6% of salary. Employer matches do not count toward your $23,500 personal limit but do count toward the $70,000 combined limit.</p>
        <p>Common match formulas include 100% of the first 3% of salary, 50% of the first 6%, or a flat dollar amount per year. Failing to contribute enough to capture the full match is one of the most costly financial mistakes available — you are effectively turning down part of your compensation.</p>
        <div class="tip-callout"><p><strong>Vesting schedules:</strong> Employer contributions may vest over time — meaning you only keep the full match after a certain number of years of service. Your own contributions are always 100% vested immediately. Check your plan documents for details.</p></div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-section">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">What happens if I contribute more than the 401(k) limit?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">Excess contributions are included in your taxable income and subject to a 6% excise tax each year they remain in the account. You must withdraw the excess amount plus any earnings by your tax filing deadline, including extensions, to avoid the penalty. Contact your plan administrator immediately if you over-contribute.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">Can I contribute to both a 401(k) and an IRA in 2025?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">Yes. Contributing to a 401(k) does not prevent you from also contributing to a traditional or Roth IRA. However, your ability to deduct traditional IRA contributions may be limited if you are covered by a workplace plan and your income exceeds certain thresholds. The 2025 IRA contribution limit is $7,000, or $8,000 if you are 50 or older.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">What is the SECURE 2.0 super catch-up contribution for 2025?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">SECURE 2.0 introduced an enhanced catch-up contribution for workers aged 60 to 63. Starting in 2025, these workers can contribute an additional $11,250 instead of the standard $7,500 catch-up. This brings their total employee limit to $34,750 for 2025.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">Do 401(k) contributions count toward Social Security taxes?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">No. Traditional 401(k) elective deferrals reduce your federal and state income tax but do not reduce FICA taxes. You still pay 6.2% Social Security and 1.45% Medicare tax on your full gross salary regardless of how much you contribute to your 401(k).</div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">What is the 401(k) contribution deadline for 2025?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">Unlike IRAs, 401(k) contributions must be made through payroll deductions during the calendar year. You cannot make a lump-sum 401(k) contribution after December 31. The deadline for 2025 contributions is your last paycheck of 2025, so adjust your deferral election well before year-end.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

